{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"465a7225-efec-4e2e-84f7-7bc40b5010f1","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Scenario | Events |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created → Activated` |\n| Sent to background | `Deactivated → Stopped` |\n| Returned to foreground | `Resumed → Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |\n| iOS background snapshot | `Backgrounding` (save state via `e.State`) |\n\n> **Tip:** `Backgrounding` is iOS-only and provides a `BackgroundingEventArgs.State` dictionary you can use to persist transient UI state.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3599492f-829b-4ce9-934f-a66469cbb728","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI - I can answer it directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":441,"requestId":"9542:B9052:137BA70:15E7D39:6A067083"},"id":"532c868c-050a-495b-a21f-dcd073586ccf","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:02:05.298Z","parentId":"bbce3f59-1199-4a9b-b4fe-9408a52564c9"}
